Reasoning: The paper deals with linguistic analysis of parliamentary debates and involves natural language processing techniques such as stance classification and pragmatics analysis. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also involves machine learning techniques for automatic detection of speech categories, which suggests sub-categories such as cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also involves social impact analysis, which suggests sub-categories such as cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.CY (Computers and Society).
